00:03:39.290 --> 00:03:44.390
So I was born in a small
village in north of Pakistan.

00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:49.850
So my story will tell
you how education

00:03:49.850 --> 00:03:54.410
is important in the
communities which are developed

00:03:54.410 --> 00:03:58.070
and in the communities
which are not developed.

00:03:58.070 --> 00:04:02.140
And the point I'm
making is that education

00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:08.010
is the only road, only tool,
to providence, to success,

00:04:08.010 --> 00:04:14.870
to human development,
to maintain and to keep

00:04:14.870 --> 00:04:17.480
our human civilization.

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:22.250
So living in a small village
in the north of Pakistan, Swat,

00:04:22.250 --> 00:04:24.260
the village I was grew.

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:28.740
And it was a small village,
not with big population.

00:04:28.740 --> 00:04:36.420
But in that village, I think
less than 50% boys went

00:04:36.420 --> 00:04:38.860
to school, and
there was no concept

00:04:38.860 --> 00:04:41.900
of girls' education-- no
concept of girls' education.

00:04:41.900 --> 00:04:44.950
You are very lucky here.

00:04:44.950 --> 00:04:49.700
I had five sisters and
we were two brothers.

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:53.980
Our parents-- like my father
and my mother, both of them--

00:04:53.980 --> 00:04:58.300
were very, very much
interested in my brother's

00:04:58.300 --> 00:05:00.390
and in my education.

00:05:00.390 --> 00:05:05.600
But they never thought
about the education

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:09.530
of the five daughters--
brilliant daughters--

00:05:09.530 --> 00:05:12.450
which they had in their home.

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:16.500
I also observed discrimination
in small things,

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:18.240
like when a chicken was cooked.

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:23.890
So the sumptuous part of the
chicken was given to the boys,

00:05:23.890 --> 00:05:26.560
and like neck and poor
parts of the chicken

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:28.660
were given to the girls.

00:05:28.660 --> 00:05:32.490
We used to take cream with milk
in the morning with the tea,

00:05:32.490 --> 00:05:34.650
and the girls only took tea.

00:05:34.650 --> 00:05:36.870
So such it kind of
discrimination--

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:42.860
it reflects the attitude and
the behavior of the society

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:47.000
towards their girls.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:52.710
So I was in-- really, when you
don't know about human rights,

00:05:52.710 --> 00:05:59.610
justice, equality, sometime
you enjoy that favoritism,

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:01.880
which is for you.

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:03.527
Like as a child,
I might not have

00:06:03.527 --> 00:06:09.170
felt that why I'm getting cream
with milk, and my sister's not.

00:06:09.170 --> 00:06:10.640
I might have felt , OK, good.

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:13.120
I'm special.

00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:16.370
But later on, when
I got education

00:06:16.370 --> 00:06:20.010
and I did my graduation,
I did my master,

00:06:20.010 --> 00:06:27.280
I realized that that
education changed me.

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:30.970
Education changed my
inner being-- inner being.

00:06:30.970 --> 00:06:36.240
And the things I was-- I
found in my childhood--

00:06:36.240 --> 00:06:40.130
like I was bullied by
some of my cousins,

00:06:40.130 --> 00:06:41.300
because of my stammering.

00:06:41.300 --> 00:06:44.830
I stammered when I talk,
so they bullied me.

00:06:44.830 --> 00:06:48.030
And I was also a little
bit discriminated

00:06:48.030 --> 00:06:51.260
because of my dark color.

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:54.950
Fair color was more
popular in the community.

00:06:54.950 --> 00:07:02.830
And I tried to wash my face
with milk, but it didn't work.

00:07:02.830 --> 00:07:10.040
So after getting
education, I thought

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:15.870
that I should not retaliate or
respond, bullying for bullying,

00:07:15.870 --> 00:07:18.000
or head for head,
or discrimination

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:19.620
for discrimination.

00:07:19.620 --> 00:07:27.170
My positive revenge was to fight
against all those injustices,

00:07:27.170 --> 00:07:29.890
inequalities, and
discriminations

00:07:29.890 --> 00:07:35.290
which exist in any form
in the human community.

00:07:35.290 --> 00:07:39.510
So my education-- I mean the
education changed my life.

00:07:39.510 --> 00:07:44.415
And when I married
Tor Pekai, she

00:07:44.415 --> 00:07:47.580
could not go to
school-- because there

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:52.090
was a school in her
small village, too.

00:07:52.090 --> 00:07:54.560
Her father took her
to school, but she

00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:56.430
was the only girl
in the classroom

00:07:56.430 --> 00:08:01.830
and all the rest were boys.

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:03.620
And in the classroom,
she used to think

00:08:03.620 --> 00:08:08.050
of our cousins, who used to play
in the fields, on the rooftops.

00:08:08.050 --> 00:08:10.160
And she said, [INAUDIBLE].

00:08:10.160 --> 00:08:13.870
I will not-- let's stop
it, because she was missing

00:08:13.870 --> 00:08:16.120
her other cousins and peers.

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:17.685
So she left school
at very early age,

00:08:17.685 --> 00:08:20.540
but nobody asked here
where are her books--

00:08:20.540 --> 00:08:23.840
why is she not studying, why
she's not really in school.

00:08:23.840 --> 00:08:26.740
So that was the end
of her education.

00:08:26.740 --> 00:08:30.380
But after marrying her, I
realized that I married her

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:32.450
because she was very beautiful.

00:08:32.450 --> 00:08:36.690
Later, I know that she's
very wise-- wiser than me--

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:39.640
very prudent, very intelligent.

00:08:39.640 --> 00:08:42.299
And then I said,
I felt very sorry

00:08:42.299 --> 00:08:45.850
that had she been educated--
she's still very good.

00:08:45.850 --> 00:08:48.230
But I was thinking
that how many women

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:52.050
we have lost their
potentials, their energies,

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:54.240
their contribution
to the community,

00:08:54.240 --> 00:08:56.250
because of not educating them.

00:08:56.250 --> 00:08:59.340
And I thought that,
if I'm a father-- long

00:08:59.340 --> 00:09:01.980
before marrying here, I
was thinking of marriage.

00:09:01.980 --> 00:09:06.010
Every young man thinks
of marriage, you know.

00:09:06.010 --> 00:09:10.290
And I was thinking that if I
marry and then I have children,

00:09:10.290 --> 00:09:15.780
I must have a daughter, and I
will name her Malala Yousafzai.

00:09:15.780 --> 00:09:21.670
Because Malalai of Maiwand was
a legendary great Afghan heroine

00:09:21.670 --> 00:09:30.390
who raised her voice against
the British army in Afghanistan,

00:09:30.390 --> 00:09:32.400
and who encouraged
the Pashtun freedom

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:35.330
fighters to go
back and fight big,

00:09:35.330 --> 00:09:37.810
with bravery, who were
fleeing from the battlefield--

00:09:37.810 --> 00:09:41.710
they bring back, and they
fought and they won battlefield.

00:09:41.710 --> 00:09:45.670
And Malala of Maiwand, she gave
her life on that battlefield.

00:09:45.670 --> 00:09:49.940
And she became a legend
in Pashtun-Afghan history.

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:53.850
So Malala had a name of
her own, because I always

00:09:53.850 --> 00:10:01.900
tell that in patriarchal or
narrow religious societies,

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:06.140
women are usually known
by their men-- mostly.

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:07.950
Even, I give an
example that when

00:10:07.950 --> 00:10:12.810
they take a woman to a doctor
and the doctor asks, OK.

00:10:12.810 --> 00:10:15.170
What is the name of the patient?

00:10:15.170 --> 00:10:18.320
And they say, OK, right--
Mr. So-and-so's daughter,

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:20.360
Mr. So-and-so's wife.

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:25.640
He feels ashamed telling the
name of his sister or his wife,

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:28.620
because even the name
is something private.

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:32.170
And I'll share an
interesting thing with you.

00:10:32.170 --> 00:10:39.610
In Arabic, women
are called [ARABIC].

00:10:39.610 --> 00:10:43.699
You know? [ARABIC] Can you
utter this word with me?

00:10:43.699 --> 00:10:44.490
AUDIENCE: [ARABIC].

00:10:44.490 --> 00:10:45.698
ZIAUDDIN YOUSAFZAI: [ARABIC].

00:10:45.698 --> 00:10:51.600
And [ARABIC] means the covered,
the hidden, the covered.

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:53.340
You understand?

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:56.370
So when you call
them the covered

00:10:56.370 --> 00:11:00.560
and the hidden, the
behind-the-scene,

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:03.550
this very word that you
give them collectively--

00:11:03.550 --> 00:11:08.060
it tells your perception
and your ideology

00:11:08.060 --> 00:11:12.430
about women, freedom,
and empowerment.

00:11:12.430 --> 00:11:15.550
So I thought that if I'm
a father, the first thing

00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:20.390
I'll do that I will
educate her very seriously.

00:11:20.390 --> 00:11:29.060
And I think that as I believe
in education, so I started

00:11:29.060 --> 00:11:31.050
a school in the Swat valley.

00:11:31.050 --> 00:11:33.800
It was an independent school,
and I started from scratch,

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:35.650
from three children.

00:11:35.650 --> 00:11:39.870
We just recited the national
anthem of Pakistan, started it,

00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:48.420
and in 2012 this school had
1,200 children-- 500 girls

00:11:48.420 --> 00:11:52.120
and some 700 boys.

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:56.460
So Malala was in
the same school,

00:11:56.460 --> 00:12:02.750
and I realized when I
was operating and running

00:12:02.750 --> 00:12:07.680
that girl's school-- because
I came close to the girls--

00:12:07.680 --> 00:12:11.930
and I realized that
how much brilliant

00:12:11.930 --> 00:12:16.090
these girls are-- the way they
think, how much critical they

00:12:16.090 --> 00:12:20.990
are in thinking, how
much confident they are.

00:12:20.990 --> 00:12:24.360
And that's why, when Taliban
banned girls' education, so

00:12:24.360 --> 00:12:26.130
we had to stand.

00:12:26.130 --> 00:12:30.140
And Malala wrote a BBC diary.

00:12:30.140 --> 00:12:33.180
She volunteered herself for a
"New York Times" documentary

00:12:33.180 --> 00:12:34.610
to raise her voice.

00:12:34.610 --> 00:12:37.200
And her voice was the
most powerful voice

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:39.130
for girls' education.

00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:43.290
And what happened later on
is that voice was so powerful

00:12:43.290 --> 00:12:48.600
that Taliban felt it is becoming
very popular in the country.

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:54.930
And rather than getting
terrified of our violence

00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:59.120
and horror, people are
listening to the peaceful voice

00:12:59.120 --> 00:13:01.380
of this girl.

00:13:01.380 --> 00:13:03.760
I mean, her voice
was more powerful

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:08.550
than the suicide attacks
and bomb blasts of Taliban.

00:13:08.550 --> 00:13:10.340
And they realized
that she should

00:13:10.340 --> 00:13:15.320
be finished, because when
you don't have any argument

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:22.060
and when you are weak in your
argument, and you're violent,

00:13:22.060 --> 00:13:26.910
then the only way you have
is to finish your opponent--

00:13:26.910 --> 00:13:30.990
or finish the person who
doesn't agree with you.

00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:34.520
But man proposes, God disposes.

00:13:34.520 --> 00:13:38.480
The voice which they wanted
to silence on a local level,

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:42.930
it become a global voice for
every child, for everybody,

00:13:42.930 --> 00:13:45.520
for the right of education.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:46.602
Thank you very much.

00:13:46.602 --> 00:13:47.310
I spoke for long.

00:13:47.310 --> 00:13:48.622
Thank you.

